## Best Practices

1. **Concise Labels**: Keep badge text short and focused (1-3 words max)
   - Use abbreviations when appropriate
   - Focus on key information only
   - All caps for consistent appearance

2. **Consistent Color Usage**: Use badge colors consistently for specific meanings
   - `badge-success` (green): Positive outcomes, improvements, completed states
   - `badge-warning` (orange): Attention required, pending actions, moderate alerts
   - `badge-error` (red): Errors, critical issues, negative trends
   - Default (blue): Neutral information, standard states
   - `badge-grey`: Secondary or less important information

3. **Appropriate Placement**: Position badges consistently in the interface
   - Right-aligned in list items
   - Vertically center-aligned with related text
   - Consistent placement within similar components

4. **Text Formatting**: Badge text is automatically uppercase
   - Enter text in normal case (`<span class="badge-text">New</span>`)
   - The CSS will transform it to uppercase
   - This maintains accessibility and allows for proper screen reader pronunciation

5. **Icon Usage**: When using icons in badges
   - Choose simple, recognizable icons
   - Use icons consistently across similar badge types
   - Ensure icon meaning is clear from context

6. **Inline Spacing**: When using badges inline with text
   - Always use the `badge-inline` class
   - Maintain consistent text flow
   - Consider line wrapping with longer text

## Common Anti-Patterns to Avoid

1. **Missing Badge-Text Wrapper**: Always wrap text inside a `badge-text` span
   ```html
   <!-- INCORRECT -->
   <span class="badge">Label</span>
   
   <!-- CORRECT -->
   <span class="badge">
       <span class="badge-text">Label</span>
   </span>
   ```

2. **Inconsistent Semantic Usage**: Don't mix badge meanings across the application
   ```html
   <!-- INCORRECT: Using success badge for warnings -->
   <span class="badge badge-success">
       <span class="badge-text">Warning</span>
   </span>
   ```

3. **Too Much Text**: Badges should be concise and not contain long text
   ```html
   <!-- INCORRECT: Too much text -->
   <span class="badge">
       <span class="badge-text">This badge contains way too much text for a badge component</span>
   </span>
   ```

4. **Custom Styling**: Avoid inline styling that overrides badge appearance
   ```html
   <!-- INCORRECT: Custom styling -->
   <span class="badge" style="background-color: pink; color: black;">
       <span class="badge-text">Custom Badge</span>
   </span>
   ```

5. **Inconsistent Element Usage**: Always use `<span>` elements for badges, not divs or other elements
   ```html
   <!-- INCORRECT: Using div instead of span -->
   <div class="badge">
       <span class="badge-text">Label</span>
   </div>
   ```

6. **Missing Icon Container**: When using icons, always wrap them in an icon container
   ```html
   <!-- INCORRECT: Direct icon without container -->
   <span class="badge badge-with-icon">
       <i class="fa-solid fa-info-circle"></i>
       <span class="badge-text">Info</span>
   </span>
   
   <!-- CORRECT -->
   <span class="badge badge-with-icon">
       <div class="icon-container">
           <i class="fa-solid fa-info-circle"></i>
       </div>
       <span class="badge-text">Info</span>
   </span>
   ```

7. **Mixed Badge Types**: Don't mix semantically opposite badge types together
   ```html
   <!-- INCORRECT: Mixing success and error -->
   <div style="display: flex; gap: var(--space-2);">
       <span class="badge badge-success">
           <span class="badge-text">Complete</span>
       </span>
       <span class="badge badge-error">
           <span class="badge-text">Failed</span>
       </span>
   </div>
   ```

